<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[189,334,416,442]" box="[189,334,416,442]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,334,416,442]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,334,416,442]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[189,1399,463,742]" box="[234,612,463,490]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[234,612,463,490]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
Light microscopy (
<figureCitation box="[468,604,463,489]" captionStart="Figs 13–26" captionStartId="4.[189,241,1885,1911]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,658,1847]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[189,1398,658,1847]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 13–26. Luticolasubcrozetensis VandeVijver et al. Light(LM) and scanning electron micrographs (SEM) of a population from Ile Saint-Paul. 13–22. LM of valve face views. 23–24. SEM of external view showing composition of striae and typical raphe structure. 25–26. SEM girdle view. Scale bars: 13‒22 =10 µm; 23‒26 = 5 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1133657/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Figs 13–22</figureCitation>
)
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[189,1399,463,742]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
Valves rhombic-lanceolate to elliptic-lanceolate and even elliptic in smaller specimens with clearly convex margins and broadly rounded, non-protracted apices. Valve dimensions (n = 25): length 12‒ 29 µm, width 7.0‒8.5 µm. Axial area linear, slightly widening towards apices and central area. Central area bow-tie shaped, wider opposite the isolated pore, bordered by shortened striae on both sides. An isolated pore present in the central area, located halfway between the valve centre and the valve margin. Raphe branches straight, bent away from the isolated pore at both proximal and distal ends. Striae radiate throughout the entire valve, 
<quantity box="[608,711,715,742]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.064" metricValueMax="4.318" metricValueMin="3.81" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" unit="in" value="16.0" valueMax="17.0" valueMin="15.0">15‒17 in</quantity>
10 µm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[189,1399,781,1095]" box="[234,768,781,808]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[234,768,781,808]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
Scanning electron microscopy (
<figureCitation box="[623,760,781,807]" captionStart="Figs 13–26" captionStartId="4.[189,241,1885,1911]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,658,1847]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[189,1398,658,1847]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 13–26. Luticolasubcrozetensis VandeVijver et al. Light(LM) and scanning electron micrographs (SEM) of a population from Ile Saint-Paul. 13–22. LM of valve face views. 23–24. SEM of external view showing composition of striae and typical raphe structure. 25–26. SEM girdle view. Scale bars: 13‒22 =10 µm; 23‒26 = 5 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1133657/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Figs 23–26</figureCitation>
)
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[189,1399,781,1095]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
Striae composed of 3–5 small, rounded to slightly elongated areolae at the apices, only 1–2 rounded areolae per stria, extending past the terminal raphe fissures on the valve face (
<figureCitation box="[1107,1195,853,879]" captionStart="Figs 13–26" captionStartId="4.[189,241,1885,1911]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,658,1847]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[189,1398,658,1847]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 13–26. Luticolasubcrozetensis VandeVijver et al. Light(LM) and scanning electron micrographs (SEM) of a population from Ile Saint-Paul. 13–22. LM of valve face views. 23–24. SEM of external view showing composition of striae and typical raphe structure. 25–26. SEM girdle view. Scale bars: 13‒22 =10 µm; 23‒26 = 5 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1133657/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
). A single row of rounded areolae present along entire valve mantle, interrupted at apices (
<figureCitation box="[1031,1118,889,916]" captionStart="Figs 13–26" captionStartId="4.[189,241,1885,1911]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,658,1847]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[189,1398,658,1847]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 13–26. Luticolasubcrozetensis VandeVijver et al. Light(LM) and scanning electron micrographs (SEM) of a population from Ile Saint-Paul. 13–22. LM of valve face views. 23–24. SEM of external view showing composition of striae and typical raphe structure. 25–26. SEM girdle view. Scale bars: 13‒22 =10 µm; 23‒26 = 5 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1133657/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
). Isolated pore rounded, slightly elongated, not associated with a stria. Central area usually bordered by one, rarely two, series of small, rounded areolae. Raphe branches straight to slightly curved. Proximal raphe endings bent to the side opposite the isolated pore, terminating into weakly developed pores. Terminal raphe fissures bent to the same side as the proximal endings terminating on the valve face, not extending onto the mantle (
<figureCitation box="[198,286,1069,1095]" captionStart="Figs 13–26" captionStartId="4.[189,241,1885,1911]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,658,1847]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[189,1398,658,1847]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 13–26. Luticolasubcrozetensis VandeVijver et al. Light(LM) and scanning electron micrographs (SEM) of a population from Ile Saint-Paul. 13–22. LM of valve face views. 23–24. SEM of external view showing composition of striae and typical raphe structure. 25–26. SEM girdle view. Scale bars: 13‒22 =10 µm; 23‒26 = 5 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1133657/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[189,498,1135,1161]" box="[189,498,1135,1161]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,498,1135,1161]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,498,1135,1161]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Ecology and distribution</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[189,1399,1182,1352]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<taxonomicName box="[189,465,1182,1208]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Diadesmidaceae" genus="Luticola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="species" species="subcrozetensis">
<emphasis box="[189,465,1182,1208]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Luticola subcrozetensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a typical sub-Antarctic and Maritime Antarctic species. Originally described from Ile de la Possession (Crozet archipelago), the species was also reported from Livingston Island (
<bibRefCitation author="Zidarova R. &amp; Kopalova K. &amp; Van der Vijver B." box="[197,440,1254,1281]" journalOrPublisher="Iconographia Diatomologica" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="1 - 504" part="24" refString="Zidarova R., Kopalova K. &amp; Van der Vijver B. 2016. Diatoms from the Antarctic region: maritime Antarctica. Iconographia Diatomologica 24: 1 - 504." title="Diatoms from the Antarctic region: maritime Antarctica" type="journal article" year="2016">
Zidarova 
<emphasis box="[312,370,1254,1280]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">et al.</emphasis>
<date box="[377,440,1254,1281]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" value="2016">2016</date>
</bibRefCitation>
), one of the major South 
<collectingRegion box="[736,931,1254,1280]" country="United Kingdom" name="Shetland Islands" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<collectingCountry box="[736,839,1254,1280]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Shetland</collectingCountry>
Islands
</collectingRegion>
, located in the southern Atlantic Ocean. The species was recently found in moss samples from Gough Island (Vinšová, unpubl. res.). It was present in samples from both Ile Saint-Paul and Ile Amsterdam.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[189,1398,1392,1455]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
The largest population was observed in a soil sample collected near the rockhopper penguin rookery of Ile Saint-Paul, at an altitude of 
<quantity box="[587,662,1428,1455]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" unit="m" value="110.0">110 m</quantity>
, hidden in cracks in the rocks that border the penguin rookery.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
